# 1ï¸âƒ£1ï¸âƒ£ HTML BLOCK & INLINE ELEMENTS

### ğŸ”¹ Block Elements

Take **full width**, start on new line.

Examples:

* `<div>`
* `<p>`
* `<h1>`

```html
<p>This is a block element</p>
```

---

### ğŸ”¹ Inline Elements

Take **only required space**, stay in same line.

Examples:

* `<span>`
* `<a>`
* `<img>`

```html
<span>Inline text</span>
```

ğŸ“Œ *Interview Question:*
**Q:** Can we convert inline to block?
**A:** Yes, using CSS `display: block;`

---

# 1ï¸âƒ£2ï¸âƒ£ HTML DIV & SPAN

### ğŸ”¹ `<div>`

Used for **layout & grouping**.

```html
<div class="card">
  Content here
</div>
```

### ğŸ”¹ `<span>`

Used for **small inline styling**.

```html
<p>This is <span style="color:red;">important</span></p>
```

ğŸ“Œ *Real-world analogy:*
**div = room**, **span = sticker inside room**

---

# 1ï¸âƒ£3ï¸âƒ£ HTML CLASSES & ID

### ğŸ”¹ class

Reusable, multiple elements.

```html
<div class="box"></div>
<div class="box"></div>
```

### ğŸ”¹ id

Unique, only one element.

```html
